{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013J7QYNc9AENRaHQS8Hw4GB","type":"tool_result","content":"1\tCREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS minipanel;\n2\t\n3\tCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS minipanel.events\n4\t(\n5\t    event_id    UUID                          DEFAULT generateUUIDv4(),\n6\t    event_name  LowCardinality(String),\n7\t    timestamp   DateTime64(3, 'UTC'),\n8\t    device_id   Nullable(String),\n9\t    user_id     Nullable(String),\n10\t    properties  String,\n11\t    ingested_at DateTime64(3, 'UTC')          DEFAULT now64()\n12\t)\n13\tENGINE = MergeTree()\n14\tORDER BY (timestamp, event_id)\n15\tPARTITION BY toYYYYMM(timestamp);\n16\t\n17\tCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS minipanel.identity_mappings\n18\t(\n19\t    device_id  String,\n20\t    user_id    String,\n21\t    created_at DateTime64(3, 'UTC') DEFAULT now64()\n22\t)\n23\tENGINE = ReplacingMergeTree(created_at)\n24\tORDER BY (device_id);\n25\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"656b7ba5-00e6-4c89-8031-4b9e0c97ac54","uuid":"d8f987f4-3655-4a08-91df-f13fe594f211","timestamp":"2026-04-15T12:14:17.802Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/riccardocaranfil/bitrefill/minipanel-blank-night-2/scripts/schema.sql","content":"CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS minipanel;\n\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS minipanel.events\n(\n    event_id    UUID                          DEFAULT generateUUIDv4(),\n    event_name  LowCardinality(String),\n    timestamp   DateTime64(3, 'UTC'),\n    device_id   Nullable(String),\n    user_id     Nullable(String),\n    properties  String,\n    ingested_at DateTime64(3, 'UTC')          DEFAULT now64()\n)\nENGINE = MergeTree()\nORDER BY (timestamp, event_id)\nPARTITION BY toYYYYMM(timestamp);\n\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS minipanel.identity_mappings\n(\n    device_id  String,\n    user_id    String,\n    created_at DateTime64(3, 'UTC') DEFAULT now64()\n)\nENGINE = ReplacingMergeTree(created_at)\nORDER BY (device_id);\n","numLines":25,"startLine":1,"totalLines":25}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01AMaz5hzTPyL8ZQ5QvCAWWL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a good understanding of the codebase. Let me look at the F4 plan more carefully and then implement:\n\n1. First, write unit tests for identity.ts\n2. Then implement identity.ts\n3. Then write integration tests\n\nFrom the plan:\n- `src/lib/identity.ts` — needs to export: `validateEvent`, `insertEvent`, `resolveIdentityMapping`, `queryEventsWithResolvedId`, `getEventsByResolvedId`\n- Unit tests: `src/lib/__tests__/identity.test.ts`\n- Integration tests: `src/lib/__tests__/identity.integration.test.ts`\n\n\nI need to check the existing test patterns to match them. Looking at how clickhouse.test.ts mocks the client, I'll need to mock the clickhouse singleton from `@/lib/clickhouse` for the identity tests. Let me sketch out the types and structure for identity.ts, including the EventInput interface and related types...\n\nDefining the error class and exported functions...\n\nNow I'm planning out the unit tests, starting with validation logic that checks for missing fields and accepts various combinations of device and user identifiers, then moving into insertion tests that verify timestamp defaults and data preservation. es caller-provided `timestamp`\n8. `insertEvent` inserts event into ClickHouse `events` table (verify mock called with correct query/values)\n9. `insertEvent` calls `resolveIdentityMapping` when both `device_id` and `user_id` are present\n10. `insertEvent` does NOT call `resolveIdentityMapping` when only `device_id` is present\n11. `insertEvent` does NOT call `resolveIdentityMapping` when only `user_id` is present\n12. `resolveIdentityMapping` inserts mapping when no existing mapping found (mock returns empty result)\n13. `resolveIdentityMapping` is a no-op when existing mapping has the same `user_id`\n14. `resolveIdentityMapping` throws `IdentityConflictError` when existing mapping has a different `user_id`\n\nFor the mock pattern, I need to mock the ClickHouse module to provide a mock client with `query`, `insert`, and `command` methods. Looking at how the ClickHouse client works, the `insert` method takes a table name, values array, and format, while the `query` method executes SQL and returns results that can be parsed as JSON.\n\nNow I'm planning out the test structure: I'll set up the mock to return controlled values for different scenarios, then write tests that verify the identity resolution logic handles conflicts correctly, inserts new mappings when needed, and skips resolution when only one identifier is present.\n\nI'm also defining the core types and error classes for the identity module—the EventInput interface for incoming data, EventRow for database records, and a custom IdentityConflictError that captures when a device is already mapped to a different user.\n\nDefining the validation function... Writing the event insertion logic... Building the query function... Writing the test file...\n\nI need to set up mocks for the clickhouse client before importing the identity module, since Vitest hoists `vi.mock` calls. Then I'll configure the mock responses for each test case—for `resolveIdentityMapping`, I need to mock the query results to return identity mappings, and for `insertEvent`, I need to mock the insert operation.\n\nThe tricky part is that `insertEvent` calls `resolveIdentityMapping` internally, so I can't directly spy on that function without restructuring. Instead, I'll verify the behavior indirectly by checking whether `mockQuery` was called when both `device_id` and `user_id` are present, since that's what `resolveIdentityMapping` uses internally. When only one identifier is present, the query shouldn't be called at all.\n\nFor the integration tests, I need to set up a test database and tables, run through the four BR-101 scenarios, and clean up between tests. I'm looking at the schema to understand what tables need to be created in the `minipanel_test` database.\n\nThe cleanest approach is to create a separate ClickHouse client configured for the test database rather than trying to override the database in individual queries, since the main client is already set up for the production database. tests I need to either:\n   a. Override the database via env vars before importing\n   b. Export functions that accept a client parameter\n   c. Use a different approach\n\nHmm, this is tricky. The identity.ts module imports the clickhouse singleton directly. For integration tests, we want to use a different database.\n\nOne approach: allow identity functions to accept an optional client, defaulting to the singleton.\n\nAnother approach: set the `CLICKHOUSE_DB` env var to `minipanel_test` before the test, and reset it after. But module imports are cached...\n\nActually, the simplest approach for integration tests is to NOT use the identity.ts functions with a test database, but instead test them by:\n1. Patching the ClickHouse client to point to the test DB\n2. Or using full table names in queries\n\nSo the integration test file needs to create test tables in `minipanel_test`, but the identity.ts module hardcodes the `minipanel` database through its singleton. The cleanest solution is probably to make the identity functions accept an optional client parameter for injection, or temporarily patch the module during tests to use a test-specific client instead. Let me think about how to handle this.\n\nOption 1: Accept a client parameter in all functions (dependency injection)\n- Cleanest but requires changing the interface\n\nOption 2: In integration tests, create a separate client for `minipanel_test` and test direct ClickHouse operations (not going through identity.ts functions)\n- This doesn't actually test the identity.ts functions\n\nOption 3: Have the integration test use the main client but operate on a test-specific database by using full table paths in identity.ts\n- Need to restructure queries\n\nOption 4: In integration tests, mock/override the module to use a test client\n- vi.doMock or vi.importActual with manipulation\n\nOption 5: Use process.env.CLICKHOUSE_DB = 'minipanel_test' before importing, and reset modules between tests\n- This requires careful module reset management\n\nI think dependency injection or the environment variable approach are most practical. For sprint 1, I'll go with accepting an optional client parameter in the identity functions—it's the cleanest pattern for ClickHouse integration tests. Though this means unit tests would need to pass the mock client explicitly, which changes how mocking works. The real issue is that if I keep the default database as `minipanel`, test data would pollute production, so I need to either inject the client or override the environment before module load. This could interfere with dev data.\n\nThe cleanest solution for a library like this is dependency injection. Let me refactor identity.ts to accept an optional client parameter, which allows tests to pass a test-scoped client pointing to `minipanel_test`. This changes the public API slightly, but the plan doesn't specify exact function signatures, so it should be fine.\n\nFor unit tests, the module mock intercepts the default singleton anyway, so they work without passing a client. For integration tests, I can pass a real client pointing to `minipanel_test` for clean separation. I'll set up the integration tests to create the `minipanel_test` database and tables before each test, then truncate the data afterward.\n\nNow I'm refactoring the identity functions to accept an optional client parameter with the singleton as the default...\n\nWriting the function signatures... Setting up the mock structure for the unit tests, where I'll create a mock query function that returns an object with a json method, and I can control what that method resolves to in each test case. I also need to think through what the `insertEvent` function should return.\n\nFor the return value, since ClickHouse won't automatically give me back the generated UUID, I'll generate it client-side using `crypto.randomUUID()` and include it in the insert statement, so the returned event object has the complete data including the event_id.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the `queryEventsWithResolvedId` function—filtering by a computed `resolved_id` value is tricky since it comes from a JOIN and can't be directly used in a WHERE clause without a subquery or HAVING clause. I'll use the full expression directly in the WHERE clause since ClickHouse supports it, and I need to handle the timestamp conversion when inserting ISO 8601 strings into DateTime64 fields.\n\nFor the integration tests, I should use unqualified table names so they work with whatever database the client is configured with. Now I'm ready to write out the three main files with the event input/row interfaces, the conflict error class, and the validation logic. I'm setting up the integration test database with a `minipanel_test` instance and tables, then truncating them between tests to handle the BR-101 scenarios. Now I need to figure out the right type for the ClickHouseClient import—checking the `@clickhouse/client` package to see if I should use the exported type directly or derive it from the `createClient` function's return type to avoid version-specific issues. I can use `typeof clickhouse` directly in function signatures since it's already a singleton, which keeps things type-safe without needing extra type imports. For the integration tests, I'll have the test client call `createClient` directly with the test database configuration.\n\nLooking at the ClickHouse client API, I need to use `command()` for DDL statements like creating and truncating tables. For test isolation, I'll truncate the tables after each test to clean up the data.\n\nNow I'm working through the BR-101 scenario: an anonymous event comes in first with just a device_id, then an identify event arrives with both device_id and user_id, which creates the mapping. When I query for that resolved_id afterward, all events from that device should return with the user_id as their resolved_id.\n\nWriting the integration tests... → should return BOTH events (retroactive)\n\nThis works because the JOIN with `identity_mappings FINAL` will resolve `dev-1` to `user@example.com`, making event 1's `resolved_id` also `user@example.com`.\n\nPerfect, this is exactly what the spec says.\n\nNow for scenario 2:\n> Two devices linked to same user → `getEventsByResolvedId(user_id)` returns events from both devices\n\n1. Insert event: `{event_name: \"Page Viewed\", device_id: \"dev-1\", user_id: \"user@test.com\"}`\n2. Insert event: `{event_name: \"Click\", device_id: \"dev-2\", user_id: \"user@test.com\"}`\n3. `getEventsByResolvedId(\"user@test.com\")` → should return both events\n\nFor scenario 3, if I try to map a device that's already linked to a different user, it should throw an `IdentityConflictError`. So inserting an event with `dev-1` and `user1@test.com`, then trying to insert another with `dev-1` and `user2@test.com` should fail with a 409 conflict.\n\nScenario 4 tests idempotency: inserting the same device-user-event combination twice shouldn't error. But there's a subtlety with ClickHouse's `ReplacingMergeTree` — deduplication happens asynchronously during merges, so I need to account for that behavior. after insert, the data is immediately visible and `FINAL` will deduplicate it in memory regardless of background merges. So querying with `FINAL` right after an insert should return the correct deduplicated result. Now I'm ready to write the code, though I need to think through one more thing about the test database setup and how the queries will be scoped.\n\nWhen I pass the test client with `database: 'minipanel_test'` to the identity functions, all the operations will automatically use that database even though the functions reference just `events` without a prefix. That should work cleanly.\n\nActually, I'm realizing there's a vitest gotcha with mocking the ClickHouse module—the factory function in `vi.mock` is hoisted and can't reference external variables unless they're prefixed with `mock`. I need to check the vitest docs on how to handle this properly.\n\nSetting up mock functions... Setting up the mock return value for the `query` method, which needs to return a `ResultSet` object with a `json()` method that resolves to an array. Now I'm thinking through the validation logic for `validateEvent` — it needs to enforce that `event_name` is a non-empty string and at least one of `device_id` or `user_id` is provided, using TypeScript's `asserts` keyword to narrow the type after validation passes. Writing validation logic... I'm working through the API design for these validation functions. The key question is whether `validateEvent` should return a typed `EventInput` or just throw on invalid data, and how that fits with `insertEvent` calling it internally. I'm leaning toward having `validateEvent` return the validated input so the type system can track it properly, then `insertEvent` accepts `EventInput` and calls `validateEvent` as a runtime safety check.\n\nLooking at what the tests actually expect, `validateEvent` needs to accept `unknown` since the tests pass in various partial objects and expect it to either validate successfully or throw. I'll keep the signature simple with `unknown` as the parameter type.\n\nWriting validation function... I need to decide on the return value for `insertEvent` — since ClickHouse doesn't give back the inserted row's UUID, I'll generate one using `crypto.randomUUID()` which is available in Node.js 14.17+. For the `properties` field, I'm thinking it should be stored as a string in the database but I need to settle on whether `EventRow` represents it as a string or parsed object.\n\nDefining the type interfaces...\n\nNow I'm working through the ClickHouse query parameters API and how to handle dynamic WHERE conditions for filtering events. I need to build parameterized queries that conditionally include filters based on what's provided, so I'm constructing the query string and params object dynamically.\n\nBuilding parameterized queries... I'm deciding between inlining the limit value or using a parameterized approach, and settling on parameterized queries with `UInt64` type for safety. Now I need to define the `IdentityConflictError` class with a 409 status code...\n\nWriting the error class...\n\nNow I'm thinking through the unit tests, specifically how to verify that `insertEvent` calls the mock with the correct table name, values structure, and format parameter using `objectContaining` matchers.\n\nFor the test that checks `resolveIdentityMapping` gets called when both device_id and user_id are present, I need to make sure the mock query returns a valid response so the identity resolution logic doesn't fail. I'm setting up default mocks in `beforeEach` where `mockQuery` returns an empty array by default, allowing the mapping insertion to proceed, and then clearing everything after each test.\n\nI'm also realizing I only need to mock `query` and `insert` methods since those are the only ones my implementation uses, unlike the broader clickhouse mock that includes `command` as well.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":638,"cache_read_input_tokens":34418,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":638},"output_tokens":13,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"656b7ba5-00e6-4c89-8031-4b9e0c97ac54","uuid":"f41593a9-f279-4ca0-ba21-be97b07e41c6"}
